===Etymology===
From {{etyl|it|en}} {{m|it|[[alla]] [[cappella]]||in the manner of the [Sistine] chapel}}, referring to non-instrumental choirs; from Latin ''[[a-]]'', ''[[ad]]'', "to", + ''[[cappella]]'', "chapel".

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˌæ.kəˈpɛl.ə/|/ˌæ.kæˈpɛl.ə/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˌɑ kə.ˈpɛl.ə/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɛlə|lang=en}}
* {{audio|En-us-a_cappella.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}

# {{lb|en|music}} In a manner of a [[choir]] with no [[instrumental]] [[accompaniment]]; literally, "in the style of the (Sistine) Chapel (in Rome)", such as a musical Mass done ''a cappella''. {{defdate|First attested in the late 19th century.}}<ref name=SOED>Brown, Lesley, ed. ''The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary.'' 5th. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2003.</ref>
#: ''Groups of teens singing ''a cappella'' on street corners got recording contracts.''
# {{lb|en|obsolete|music}} In ''[[alla breve]]'' time.

